Here are best-pracices for our test files:

Update to match:

Import neccessary test functions from vitest:

```
import { describe, test, expect, beforeAll, afterAll } from "vitest";
```


Test Names:
Test names should be plain-text, and terse active voice expressions of the tested behavior.

DO NOT begin test titles with "should". Just say what it does, assertively.

Use [TestHttpServer.ts](mdc:lib/transcode/tests/TestHttpServer.ts) to serve real test files.

Test Structure & Organization
Tests should describe expected behavior, not implementation history or refactoring process
Use descriptive test names that clearly state what behavior is being verified
Organize tests by functional behavior, not by development phases or file structure
Tests must be self-contained and independently understandable
Group tests by: core functionality, input handling, data consistency, error scenarios, utilities, performance, integration
Test-Driven Development Process
Write comprehensive test suite before consolidating code
Run tests with focused execution using appropriate test runner flags
Establish green baseline with existing implementations before changes
Use real services and minimal mocking (prefer real HTTP servers, databases, file systems)
Validate cross-implementation consistency when multiple approaches exist
Test both success and failure paths for all public interfaces
Test Content Guidelines
Assert on expected behavior and outcomes, not implementation details
Test error scenarios with actual expected behavior, not assumptions
Include edge cases: boundary conditions, different data formats, various input sizes
Validate data structure integrity and contracts
Test utility functions with both valid and invalid inputs
Verify integration points work with real dependencies
Code Consolidation Rules
Only consolidate after comprehensive test coverage exists
Update all import statements systematically after consolidation
Remove old files only after verifying all tests pass
Run integration tests to ensure no downstream breakage
Maintain identical external API during consolidation
Preserve all existing functionality during refactoring
Error Handling in Tests
Match current implementation behavior during baseline, even if suboptimal
Document actual vs expected behavior in test descriptions
Test both graceful degradation and hard failures appropriately
Cover network failures, file system errors, malformed data, and resource constraints
Documentation & Comments
Avoid process-oriented comments in final code
Don't include change history or refactoring steps in consolidated code
Focus comments on business purpose and behavior, not development process
Tests should serve as living documentation of expected behavior

TESTS SERVE AS A SYSTEM TO IMPROVE AND MAINTAIN OUR ABILITY TO CHANGE SOURCE CODE IN THE FUTURE